snippet.textDisplay: 30 May 2003: "Fred Hui, MD believes that administering vitamin C intravenously is a treatment worth trying. And he'd like to see people admitted to hospital for the pneumonia-like virus treated with the vitamin intravenously while also receiving the usual drugs for SARS. 'I appeal to hospitals to try this for people who already have SARS,' says Hui. Members of the public would also do well to build up their levels of vitamin C, he says, adding that there is nothing to lose in trying it. 'This is one of the most harmless substances there is,' Hui states. 'There used to be concern about kidney stones, but that was theoretical. It was never borne out in an actual case.' Hui says he has found intravenous vitamin C effective in his medical practice with patients who have viral illnesses.

snippet.textDisplay:
Everyone saying we need a "cure" for this please realize it is a virus. It is extremely difficult and potentially impossible if it mutates too much to make a "cure". Antiviral medication doesn't so much cure you as it stops the virus from reproducing. So any damage to the body or existing virus cells will still have to be repaired/ fought off by the host.
There are some promising in-lab test's that show Remdesivir and Chloroquine to be effective at stopping the reproduction of 2019-NCoV. But we are years away from that being a viable and accepted treatment.
For now we can only treat the symptoms while the hots immune system fights it off. The best we can do in a somewhat timely manner is make a vaccine for it limiting the spread but.. Unfortunately current estimates put that at 1.5-3 months away from synthesizing. At which point It can began trials and assuming all goes well mass production can potentially begin within 2020... But most, especially in lower population areas/ countries will likely not see it until 2021.
